result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Rudy A Chagoya in court with attorney James C. Koppelman.  Donald J. Dunphy appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Judge will be handling the Branch I cases also - Also calling 13CF307, 14CF202, 14CF235, 14CF238 and 14CF240 - Plea questionnaire provided to court - Plea no contest to count 1 & 3 in 13CF276 - Waiver of rights and tendering plea - Waiver free and voluntary - Factual basis exists for plea - Found guilty by court - Statements by Koppelman regarding witnesses appearing on behalf of the state - Koppelman states he is limited as to to how can respond - Court questions counsel - Count 2,4,5 DRI - 13CF307 will be dismissed outright - Court will adjourn for sentencing - Court would like meeting set up between law enforcement and defedant prior to sentencing - Koppelman is requesting bond be modified if the sentencing is put off - Court will not lift the no contact unless Ms. Miller and Probation agent both agree - State believes 2 hours will be needed for sentencing - Arguments by Koppelman regarding bond - Response by Dunphy - Bond will remain as previously set  Sentencing hearing scheduled for December 19, 2014 at 10:00 am.
